---
/**
 * Problem/Solution Guide: Natural Disasters and Expat Insurance
 *
 * Health insurance considerations during earthquakes, hurricanes, and other natural disasters abroad.
 */

import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Natural Disasters and Expat Health Insurance: Coverage When Disaster Strikes";
const description = "How health insurance works during natural disasters abroad. Coverage for disaster-related injuries, evacuation, when local healthcare is overwhelmed, and preparing for emergencies.";

const tocItems = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Disasters and Coverage" },
  { id: "what-covered", label: "What's Covered" },
  { id: "evacuation", label: "Disaster Evacuation" },
  { id: "overwhelmed", label: "Overwhelmed Healthcare" },
  { id: "specific-disasters", label: "Disaster Types" },
  { id: "preparation", label: "Preparation Steps" },
  { id: "during-disaster", label: "During a Disaster" },
  { id: "aftermath", label: "The Aftermath" },
  { id: "faq", label: "FAQs" },
];

const disasterColumns = [
  { key: 'disaster_type', header: 'Disaster Type' },
  { key: 'health_risks', header: 'Common Health Risks' },
  { key: 'insurance_concern', header: 'Key Insurance Concern' },
];

const disasterRows = [
  { disaster_type: 'Earthquake', health_risks: 'Crush injuries, trauma, aftershock injuries', insurance_concern: 'Overwhelmed hospitals, evacuation' },
  { disaster_type: 'Hurricane/Typhoon', health_risks: 'Injuries, flooding illness, power outages', insurance_concern: 'Airport closures, evacuation timing' },
  { disaster_type: 'Flooding', health_risks: 'Drowning, waterborne illness, injury', insurance_concern: 'Access to care, contaminated water' },
  { disaster_type: 'Wildfire', health_risks: 'Burns, smoke inhalation, respiratory', insurance_concern: 'Evacuation routes, air quality' },
  { disaster_type: 'Volcanic eruption', health_risks: 'Burns, respiratory, trauma', insurance_concern: 'Airspace closures, evacuation' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline="Natural Disasters & Insurance"
  subheadline="Earthquakes, hurricanes, floods, wildfires—natural disasters can strike anywhere. When they do, your health insurance needs to work even when local healthcare is overwhelmed and normal systems break down."
  canonicalPath="/guides/natural-disasters-insurance"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/guides/natural-disasters-hero.png"
>
  <article class="prose max-w-none">

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <p class="lead">
      You're living abroad when the earthquake hits. Or a Category 4 hurricane makes landfall. Or flooding devastates your city. Suddenly, healthcare systems are overwhelmed, hospitals are damaged, and you need to know: does my insurance work when everything else has broken down?
    </p>

    <p>
      Natural disasters create unique healthcare challenges for expats. Local facilities may be destroyed or overwhelmed. Normal access to care disappears. Evacuation becomes necessary but difficult. Your insurance's disaster response becomes critically important.
    </p>

    <p>
      This guide covers how health insurance works during natural disasters, what's typically covered, the critical importance of evacuation coverage, and how to prepare before disaster strikes.
    </p>

    <!-- Disasters and Coverage -->
    <section id="overview">
      <h2>Natural Disasters and Insurance Coverage</h2>

      <h3>Most Policies Cover Disaster Injuries</h3>
      <p>
        Standard international health insurance covers injuries from natural disasters. If you're hurt in an earthquake, your medical treatment is covered like any other injury. The cause being a natural disaster doesn't typically create exclusions.
      </p>

      <h3>The Real Challenge Isn't Coverage—It's Access</h3>
      <p>
        During major disasters, the problem usually isn't whether insurance will pay—it's whether you can access care at all. Hospitals may be damaged, overwhelmed, or unreachable. This is where evacuation coverage becomes essential.
      </p>

      <h3>Infrastructure Breakdown</h3>
      <p>
        Disasters disrupt everything: hospitals, roads, airports, communication. Even with excellent insurance, reaching care requires infrastructure that may not be functioning. Plan for scenarios where normal pathways don't work.
      </p>

      <h3>Timing Matters</h3>
      <p>
        Some evacuations need to happen before the disaster (hurricanes with warning) or immediately after (earthquake aftermath). Delayed response can mean delayed care—hours matter for serious injuries.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- What's Covered -->
    <section id="what-covered">
      <h2>What Insurance Covers</h2>

      <ComparisonTable columns={disasterColumns} rows={disasterRows} />

      <h3>Medical Treatment</h3>
      <p>
        Treatment for disaster-related injuries is covered: trauma care, surgery, hospitalization, follow-up treatment. Whether you're hurt by falling debris, flooding, or fire—your medical care is covered like any other injury.
      </p>

      <h3>Emergency Medical Evacuation</h3>
      <p>
        If local facilities can't treat you adequately, evacuation coverage transports you to appropriate care elsewhere. This is the critical coverage for disasters—when local hospitals are overwhelmed or destroyed.
      </p>

      <h3>Security Evacuation</h3>
      <p>
        Some policies include security evacuation—evacuation when the situation is dangerous, not just when you're medically unable to get care. This covers evacuation when staying becomes unsafe even if you're not injured.
      </p>

      <h3>Typical Exclusions</h3>
      <p>
        Few policies exclude natural disasters from medical coverage. However, some travel policies exclude "known events"—if you travel to a destination after a hurricane warning, coverage may not apply. International health insurance typically doesn't have this limitation.
      </p>

      <h3>Property Loss</h3>
      <p>
        Health insurance doesn't cover property damage from disasters—that's home/renters insurance or contents insurance. Your health insurance covers you, not your belongings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Disaster Evacuation -->
    <section id="evacuation">
      <h2>Evacuation Coverage</h2>

      <h3>Medical Evacuation</h3>
      <p>
        Medical evacuation covers transport to appropriate medical facilities when local care is inadequate. During disasters, this becomes essential—local hospitals may be destroyed, overwhelmed, or unreachable.
      </p>

      <h3>Security/Non-Medical Evacuation</h3>
      <p>
        Some policies include security evacuation—getting you out when the situation is dangerous, even if you don't have a medical emergency. This covers: civil unrest following disasters, ongoing danger, or breakdown of civil order.
      </p>

      <h3>Evacuation During Active Disasters</h3>
      <p>
        Evacuation during an active disaster (hurricane approaching, ongoing earthquake aftershocks) is complex. Airports may close; roads may be blocked. Insurers coordinate with local authorities and may evacuate before or after peak danger.
      </p>

      <h3>Evacuation Limits</h3>
      <p>
        Verify your evacuation coverage limits. Mass disaster evacuations are expensive; costs add up when commercial options aren't available. Look for policies with $250,000+ or unlimited evacuation coverage.
      </p>

      <h3>Pre-Evacuation for Known Disasters</h3>
      <p>
        For predictable disasters (hurricanes with days of warning), you can often evacuate commercially before the disaster hits. Insurance may not cover pre-emptive evacuation, but personal evacuation before disaster is often the best choice.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA Box -->
    <CTABox
      variant="highlight"
      title="Are You Covered for Disasters?"
      description="Compare international health insurance with strong evacuation coverage. Ensure your policy works when local healthcare fails."
      buttonText="Compare Plans"
      buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    />

    <!-- Overwhelmed Healthcare -->
    <section id="overwhelmed">
      <h2>When Local Healthcare Is Overwhelmed</h2>

      <h3>Hospital Capacity Crisis</h3>
      <p>
        Major disasters can create hundreds or thousands of casualties simultaneously. Local hospitals—even undamaged ones—become overwhelmed. Your insurance covers treatment, but wait times for non-critical care can be extreme.
      </p>

      <h3>Triage Reality</h3>
      <p>
        During mass casualty events, hospitals triage by severity. Your insurance doesn't change your triage priority. If your injury isn't immediately life-threatening, you may wait while critical cases are treated first.
      </p>

      <h3>When to Request Evacuation</h3>
      <p>
        If local facilities can't adequately treat you—whether due to damage, overcrowding, or lack of specialists—contact your insurer about evacuation. Don't wait for the situation to worsen.
      </p>

      <h3>Private vs. Public Facilities</h3>
      <p>
        During disasters, even private hospitals may be overwhelmed. Your insurance's network access doesn't guarantee immediate care when everyone needs help simultaneously.
      </p>

      <h3>Continuity of Care</h3>
      <p>
        If you have ongoing conditions requiring regular care (dialysis, cancer treatment, etc.), disasters disrupt that care. Have a plan for maintaining critical treatment or evacuating to where you can receive it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Specific Disaster Types -->
    <section id="specific-disasters">
      <h2>Specific Disaster Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Earthquakes</h3>
      <p>
        Earthquakes strike without warning. Injuries are often trauma-related: crush injuries, falls, cuts. Aftershocks continue for days or weeks. Hospitals may be damaged. Evacuation may be necessary if medical infrastructure is destroyed.
      </p>

      <h3>Hurricanes and Typhoons</h3>
      <p>
        Hurricanes provide warning—days to prepare or evacuate. Consider leaving before landfall. After the storm: injuries from debris, flooding illness, power outages affecting hospitals. Airport recovery may take days.
      </p>

      <h3>Flooding</h3>
      <p>
        Floods create immediate drowning risk and later waterborne illness (contaminated water, infections). Healthcare access may be blocked by water. Hospitals in flood zones may evacuate patients before you can reach them.
      </p>

      <h3>Wildfires</h3>
      <p>
        Wildfires spread rapidly. Evacuation timing is critical—don't wait. Health risks include burns and severe smoke inhalation. Air quality may be dangerous for days or weeks after fires are contained.
      </p>

      <h3>Volcanic Eruptions</h3>
      <p>
        Volcanic events range from ash fall to pyroclastic flows. Ashfall creates respiratory issues; proximity creates severe danger. Airspace may close, complicating evacuation. Respiratory coverage becomes important.
      </p>

      <h3>Tsunamis</h3>
      <p>
        Tsunamis follow earthquakes or underwater landslides. Coastal areas face wall-of-water impact. If you survive the initial wave, trauma injuries and drowning are primary concerns. Coastal healthcare may be destroyed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Preparation Steps -->
    <section id="preparation">
      <h2>Preparing Before Disaster</h2>

      <h3>Know Your Region's Risks</h3>
      <p>
        Understand what natural disasters affect your location: earthquake zones, hurricane belts, flood plains, fire-prone areas. Different disasters require different preparation and have different warning times.
      </p>

      <h3>Verify Evacuation Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        Check your policy's evacuation coverage: limits, what triggers evacuation, security vs. medical evacuation, and the coordination process. Don't wait until you need it to understand how it works.
      </p>

      <h3>Know Emergency Contacts</h3>
      <p>
        Have your insurer's emergency line readily accessible—not buried in email or documents you can't access without power. Memorize or keep on paper: emergency numbers, policy numbers, relevant contacts.
      </p>

      <h3>Emergency Supplies</h3>
      <p>
        Beyond insurance, have emergency supplies: first aid kit, medications for several weeks, emergency contact information, copies of important documents, cash for when cards don't work.
      </p>

      <h3>Evacuation Plan</h3>
      <p>
        Have a personal evacuation plan: where would you go, how would you get there, what would you take. For hurricanes and fires with warning, know when you'd leave and where you'd go—don't rely on last-minute decisions.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- During a Disaster -->
    <section id="during-disaster">
      <h2>During a Disaster</h2>

      <h3>Safety First</h3>
      <p>
        Your immediate priority is surviving the disaster. Insurance matters after you're safe. Follow local emergency guidance, shelter appropriately, and don't take unnecessary risks.
      </p>

      <h3>Contact Your Insurer Early</h3>
      <p>
        If you have injuries or anticipate needing evacuation, contact your insurer as soon as safely possible. Early contact helps them begin coordination—evacuation logistics take time to arrange.
      </p>

      <h3>Document What Happens</h3>
      <p>
        If possible, document injuries and circumstances. Photos, notes, medical records—these help with claims later. But don't prioritize documentation over safety.
      </p>

      <h3>Follow Insurer Guidance</h3>
      <p>
        Your insurer's emergency team coordinates care and evacuation. Follow their guidance about where to go for treatment, when evacuation will happen, and what to do while waiting.
      </p>

      <h3>Embassy Registration</h3>
      <p>
        Register with your home country's embassy during major disasters. They can assist with evacuation coordination, communications with family, and documentation issues.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- The Aftermath -->
    <section id="aftermath">
      <h2>After the Disaster</h2>

      <h3>Ongoing Medical Needs</h3>
      <p>
        Disasters create ongoing medical needs: follow-up care for injuries, mental health support, medication replacement. Your insurance covers these continuing needs, not just initial emergency treatment.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health Impact</h3>
      <p>
        Disasters cause psychological trauma. PTSD, anxiety, depression following disasters are real and treatable. Ensure your insurance covers mental health care—you may need it more than you expect.
      </p>

      <h3>Infrastructure Recovery</h3>
      <p>
        Healthcare infrastructure takes time to recover. Hospitals may operate at reduced capacity for weeks or months. You may need to travel for specialist care or continue treatment that was interrupted.
      </p>

      <h3>Returning to Normal</h3>
      <p>
        Eventually, normal healthcare access returns. Your ongoing care transitions from emergency mode to regular appointments. Keep documentation from the disaster period for continuity.
      </p>

      <h3>Claims After the Dust Settles</h3>
      <p>
        File claims for disaster-related expenses. Keep receipts, documentation, and medical records. Insurers expect some delays during disasters but will want documentation when the situation stabilizes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Does insurance cover injuries from natural disasters?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Standard international health insurance covers injuries regardless of cause, including natural disasters. Earthquakes, hurricanes, floods—if you're injured, treatment is covered.
      </p>

      <h3>What if the hospital is destroyed or overwhelmed?</h3>
      <p>
        This is where evacuation coverage matters. If local facilities can't treat you, your insurer arranges transport to appropriate care elsewhere. Contact them to initiate evacuation.
      </p>

      <h3>Does insurance cover evacuation before a hurricane hits?</h3>
      <p>
        Security evacuation coverage may cover pre-emptive evacuation when danger is imminent. Many people evacuate commercially before hurricanes—cheaper and easier than emergency evacuation after. Check your specific policy.
      </p>

      <h3>What if I can't reach my insurer during the disaster?</h3>
      <p>
        Focus on safety first. Get care where available—insurers understand disaster situations. Contact them as soon as you can. They'll work with you on claims even without immediate authorization.
      </p>

      <h3>Are there natural disaster exclusions in policies?</h3>
      <p>
        International health insurance typically doesn't exclude natural disasters. Some travel insurance excludes "known events" (traveling to a destination after warnings). Check your specific policy terms.
      </p>

      <h3>What about ongoing conditions during disasters?</h3>
      <p>
        If you need regular treatment (dialysis, chemotherapy, etc.), disaster disruption is serious. Have a plan: extra medication supply, alternative treatment locations, or early evacuation for continuity of care.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <section>
      <h2>Prepared for the Worst</h2>
      <p>
        Natural disasters are unpredictable but not unplannable. Living in earthquake zones, hurricane regions, or flood-prone areas means accepting some risk—and mitigating it through preparation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Strong health insurance with robust evacuation coverage is essential. But so is personal preparation: knowing your risks, having supplies, having an evacuation plan, and understanding how to access help when normal systems fail.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most expats never experience major disasters. But those who do are grateful for proper coverage and preparation. Don't wait until the earthquake hits to check your policy.
      </p>
    </section>

  </article>
</PageShell>
